We shall only transfer your Personal Information to the Overseas Recipient in accordance with Relevant Laws and Regulations and, where necessary, with your separate consent.
We require the Overseas Recipient of your Personal Information to:
Process Personal Information only in accordance with the agreed purpose, method and scope of the transfer and the agreed purpose and method of Personal Information Processing by the Overseas Recipient.
Inform us of the place and period of data retention abroad.
Take certain measures for handling outbound data after the retention period expires, the agreed purpose is completed, or the agreements terminate.
Not make onward transfers of Personal Information to other organizations or individuals.
Inform Infineon when there is a substantial change in its actual control or business scope or when the data security protection policies and regulations of the country or region where it is located and the network security environment changes, as well as other force majeure circumstances that make it difficult to ensure data security.
Take appropriate emergency measures to safeguard your Personal Information when it is tampered with, destroyed, leaked, lost, transferred, illegally obtained, or illegally used.
6. Storage of Personal Information
Unless Relevant Laws and Regulations stipulate longer retention periods, we only store your Personal Information for the minimum period necessary for achieving the
"Purposes of Processing PI"
described in this Addendum.
After the retention period expires, we will delete or anonymize your Personal Information in accordance with Relevant Laws and Regulations. If deleting your Personal Information is technically difficult, we will stop all Processing activities other than storing your Personal Information and take necessary security measures.
7. Security of Personal Information
Data protection has a high priority for Infineon and its subsidiaries. We use various technical and organizational measures to protect your Personal Information. To understand more about how we protect your Personal Information, please see
https://www.infineon.com/cms/en/about-infineon/sustainability/DPMS/?redirId=189805
and
https://www.infineon.com/cms/en/about-infineon/privacy-policy/#general-information-on-data-protection-privacy-at-infineon
.
8. How we use Cookies
We use Cookies as well as similar technologies. Upon your first visit to our website, you will have the choice to consent to our use of performance and marketing Cookies. To understand more about your rights or to adjust your Cookie consent settings, please see our section about
Cookies
.
9. Your Data Subject rights
9.1. Your rights over your Personal Information
Subject to Relevant Laws and Regulations, you have the following rights over your Personal Information:
Right to request access to and copies of your Personal Information.
Right to information about and to decide on our Processing.
Right to restrict or deny our Processing of your Personal Information.
Right to seek the transfer of your Personal Information to a third party under Relevant Laws and Regulations.
Right to request the rectification of your Personal Information.
Right to request the completion of your Personal Information.
Right to request the erasure of your Personal Information.
Right to unsubscribe to personalized marketing messages.
Right to request an explanation of automated decisions that have a material impact on your rights and interests.
Right to refuse decisions solely made by automated means that have a material impact on your rights and interests.
Right to request an explanation of our Personal Information Processing rules.
Right to require a copy of the Contract concluded between the Overseas Recipient and Infineon. If any trade secret or confidential business information is involved, relevant content in the copy of the Contract may be appropriately redacted.
9.2. Your Rights as a Third-Party Beneficiary
Due to the necessity of Infineon global business operations, we need to transfer your Personal Information to the Overseas Recipient. To protect your Personal Information rights and interests, we sign the Standard Contract for Outbound Transfer of Personal Information ("Contract") formulated by the Cyberspace Administration of China with the Overseas Recipient. You will be a third-party beneficiary under the Contract and enjoy relevant rights, if you do not expressly refuse these rights within 30 days. Please rest assured that the Contract does not impose any liability on you. Your rights as a third-party beneficiary under the Contract include, but are not limited to:
Right to know about, decide on, restrict and refuse the Processing of your outbound Personal Information, the right to access, make copies of, correct, supplement and delete your outbound Personal Information, as well as other rights stipulated by Relevant Laws and Regulations;
Right to exercise the above rights over your outbound Personal Information by making a request to us and/or the Overseas Recipient using the contact details set out in this Addendum;
Right to assert the above rights by filing a complaint with a Regulatory Authority or filing a lawsuit with a competent Chinese People's Court.
If you do not want to be a third-party beneficiary under the Contract, please contact us within 30 days using the details provided in in Section 10.
"How to contact us"
.
9.3. How to exercise your rights
If you would like to exercise any of the above rights, understand how we use your Personal Information, or have any questions about this Addendum, please contact us using the details provided in the Section 10.
"How to contact us"
below.
You also have the right to withdraw your consent to our Processing of your Personal Information carried out based on your consent. If you wish to withdraw your consent to our Processing of your Personal Information, contact us using the details provided in Section 10 below. Please note that the withdrawal of your consent does not affect the validity of any activity of Processing of your Personal Information already carried out before the withdrawal of your consent.
If you would like to exercise any of the above rights against any Third Party or the Overseas Recipient, please contact them directly using the information in Sections 5.2 and 5.3 above.
